  "target_response": {
    "text": "Early waking is costing you real sleep: last night's 5.9 hours was well below your sleep need of 7.3 hours. Even your 7-day average of 6.4 hours runs short of that need. Notably, your efficiency is 91% — once you're asleep, you sleep well — so this is a duration problem, not a quality one, and the usual fix is anchoring your body clock rather than trying harder in bed. Two moves: get bright outdoor light within half an hour of waking, and resist going to bed extra early tonight — a consistent, slightly later bedtime usually consolidates the night and drags the wake-up later with it. Give that two weeks before judging it; body-clock shifts are slow but they stick.",
